  "prompt": "What is the difference between a notarized and certified document?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between notarized and certified documents:\n\nNotarized Document:\n- Signed and stamped by a licensed notary public\n- Verifies the identity of the person signing the document\n- Confirms the person signed willingly and voluntarily\n- Provides an official witness to the signature\n- Common for legal and financial documents\n\nCertified Document:\n- Authenticated by an authorized official or organization\n- Confirms the document is a true, accurate copy of the original\n- Often used for academic, professional, or government records\n- Typically issued by the original issuing institution\n- Shows the document is genuine and unaltered\n\nMain distinctions:\n- Notarization focuses on signature verification\n- Certification focuses on document authenticity\n- Different purposes and official processes\n- Different types of authorized officials involved\n\nExamples:\n- Notarized: Power of attorney, real estate documents\n- Certified: Diploma, professional license, birth certificate\n\nBoth serve to add credibility and official recognition to documents, but through different means.",
